Hi Emily! Early workouts plus tight writing slots call for a super-simple template and a few go-to tricks. Try this minimal setup:

\documentclass[11pt]{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage{graphicx}
\usepackage{booktabs}
\begin{document}
\section{Results}
Here’s a table:
\begin{table}[h]
  \centering
  \begin{tabular}{lcr}
    \toprule
    Item & Qty & Price \\
    \midrule
    A & 10 & \$5.00 \\
    B & 3 & \$12.50 \\
    \bottomrule
  \end{tabular}
  \caption{Sample data}
\end{table}

And a figure:
\begin{figure}[h]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{myplot.pdf}
  \caption{My chart}
\end{figure}

\end{document}

Three quick tips:
1. Always use [h] or [H] to force placement near the text you edit.  
2. Load booktabs for clean tables.  
3. Keep a snippets file with your favorite table/figure blocks—copy-paste and fill in data.

This template compiles in seconds, so you can focus on writing after your spin class!

Absolutely! Here’s a step-by-step guide to importing your Peloton CSV data and creating a polished plot in Overleaf using PGFPlots:

1. Prepare your CSV
   • Ensure your file (e.g. peloton.csv) has headers: ‘time’, ‘cadence’, ‘resistance’, ‘output’. 
   • Upload it to your Overleaf project.

2. Load packages in your preamble:
   \usepackage{pgfplots}   % Main plotting library
   \usepackage{csvsimple}  % For CSV data handling
   \pgfplotsset{compat=1.17, width=10cm, height=6cm}

3. Create the plot environment:
   \begin{figure}[ht]
     \centering
     \begin{tikzpicture}
       \begin{axis}[
         xlabel=Time (min),
         ylabel=Value,
         grid=major,
         legend pos=outer north east,
         cycle list name=plotmarks
       ]
       % Cadence curve
       \addplot table[x=time,y=cadence,col sep=comma] {peloton.csv};
       \addlegendentry{Cadence (RPM)}
       % Resistance curve
       \addplot table[x=time,y=resistance,col sep=comma] {peloton.csv};
       \addlegendentry{Resistance}
       % Output curve
       \addplot table[x=time,y=output,col sep=comma] {peloton.csv};
       \addlegendentry{Output (Watts)}
       \end{axis}
     \end{tikzpicture}
     \caption{Peloton ride metrics over time}
     \label{fig:peloton_metrics}
   \end{figure}

4. Styling tips:
   • Use ‘cycle list name=plotmarks’ or define your own color list for consistency.
   • Adjust axis limits with ‘xmin’, ‘xmax’ or ‘ymin’, ‘ymax’ for zoom.
   • Tweak grid style: ‘grid style=dashed’ for a lighter look.

5. Compile and review. Overleaf will render and you can fine-tune labels, legend placement, or font sizes. Now you have a professional, data-driven plot right in your LaTeX report!
